# Service object guidelines

## Class structure
- A service has **one public method** — `#call`.
- All other logic lives in **private** methods.
- Place the class in a **domain-grouping module**, e.g. `Orders::SubmitOrderService`, `Invoices::Infakt::CreateInvoiceService`.

## Invocation
- On the class: `extend Utils::CallableObject` (`lib/utils/callable_object.rb`).
- Usage: `SomeModule::SomeService.call(...)` instead of `SomeService.new(...).call`.

## Operation status (no exceptions from the service)
- `include ServiceStatus` (`app/services/concerns/service_status.rb`).
- **Do not raise** from `#call` as the primary error mechanism — return a result and signal status via `success?` / `errors`.
- On failure: append to `errors` (e.g. private `handle_error`) and return `nil` or another agreed-upon “empty” result.
- Callers check `service.success?` and optionally `service.errors`.

## Pattern

```ruby
module Orders
  class ExampleService
    extend Utils::CallableObject
    include ServiceStatus

    def initialize(order:)
      @order = order
    end

    def call
      result = do_work
      result
    rescue StandardError => e
      handle_error(e.message)
    end

    private

    def handle_error(message)
      errors << message
      nil
    end
  end
end
```
